- `preamble.tex` — all `\\usepackage` and global settings\n- `macros.tex` — all `\\newcommand` definitions (sourced from preamble)\n- `chapters/` subdirectory:\n  - `00-frontmatter.tex` (title page, dedication, preface)\n  - `01-categories.tex`\n  - `02-functors.tex`\n  - `03-natural-transformations.tex`\n  - `04-limits-and-colimits.tex`\n  - `05-adjoints.tex`\n  - `06-monads.tex`\n  - `07-kan-extensions.tex`\n  - `08-enriched-categories.tex` (optional advanced chapter)\n  - `appendix-A-set-theory.tex`\n  - `appendix-B-logic.tex`\n- `figures/` subdirectory — conventions for naming and organizing tikz-cd figures vs. standalone `.tex` figure files\n- `bibliography.bib` — BibTeX database\n- `index-entries.tex` or inline `\\index{}` conventions\n- `Makefile` or `latexmkrc` — build automation (explain latexmk workflow with biber)\n- `.gitignore` for LaTeX projects\n\nShow the tree as a proper ASCII/Markdown tree, then annotate each file/directory with its purpose and key contents.\n\nAlso describe the build workflow: `latexmk -pdf -pvc main.tex`, the biber run, index generation with `makeindex` or `xindy`.\n\n---\n\nFormat your output as clean Markdown with level-2 (`##`) headers for Section 1 and Section 6, and level-3 (`###`) subheaders within each. Be concrete and specific — include actual LaTeX code blocks where helpful. This will go directly into a production plan document.","teammate_id":"latex-specialist@category-theory-book-plan","agent_id":"latex-specialist@category-theory-book-plan","agent_type":"researcher","model":"sonnet","name":"latex-specialist","color":"blue","tmux_session_name":"in-process","tmux_window_name":"in-process","tmux_pane_id":"in-process","team_name":"category-theory-book-plan","is_splitpane":false,"plan_mode_required":false}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Vn1eFbYijMXLDAR9A3m9Zy","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_017aYiHgyp9S9VnBu1zYiTcx","name":"Task","input":{"description":"Draft math/editorial content sections","subagent_type":"researcher","team_name":"category-theory-book-plan","name":"math-editorial-specialist","prompt":"You are a mathematical editor and category theory expert on a team producing a comprehensive editorial plan for a graduate-level LaTeX book on category theory. Your job is to draft FOUR sections of the plan in detail. Write your output as Markdown — thorough, specific, and production-ready. Do NOT write to disk; just produce the text.\n\n---\n\n## SECTION 2: Book Architecture\n\n### Chapter Structure\nProvide a detailed chapter-by-chapter outline including:\n- **Chapter 1: Categories** — Objects and morphisms, composition and identity axioms, first examples (Set, Grp, Top, Vect, posets, monoids as one-object categories), isomorphisms, groupoids, the category Cat\n- **Chapter 2: Functors** — Covariant and contravariant, full/faithful/essentially surjective, forgetful functors, free functors, representable functors (preview), functor categories\n- **Chapter 3: Natural Transformations** — Definition, components, naturality squares, natural isomorphisms, the Yoneda lemma (full proof) and its philosophical significance, Yoneda embedding\n- **Chapter 4: Limits and Colimits** — Products, coproducts, equalizers, pullbacks, pushouts, terminal/initial objects, the general definition, examples across categories, preservation by functors\n- **Chapter 5: Adjoint Functors** — Unit and counit, triangle identities, hom-set definition and equivalence with unit/counit, examples (free/forgetful, products/diagonals, geometric realization/singular, sheafification), RAPL theorem\n- **Chapter 6: Monads** — From adjunctions, algebras over a monad, Eilenberg–Moore and Kleisli categories, Beck's monadicity theorem\n- **Chapter 7: Kan Extensions** — Left and right Kan extensions, pointwise Kan extensions, density, \"all concepts are Kan extensions\"\n- **Chapter 8: Enriched Categories** (optional/advanced) — V-categories, V-functors, weighted limits, brief treatment\n- **Appendix A: Set-Theoretic Foundations** — Universes, Grothendieck universes, ZFC vs. ETCS, small vs. locally small categories\n- **Appendix B: Logic and Proof Techniques** — Brief review for readers from non-logic backgrounds\n\n### Front Matter\nDescribe in detail:\n- Title page (title, subtitle if any, author(s), date, publisher/series)\n- Copyright/colophon page\n- Dedication page\n- Preface (purpose of the book, intended audience, how to use it, acknowledgments)\n- Table of Contents\n- List of Notation (a formatted table of all symbols introduced)\n- Possibly: List of Theorems (using thmtools)\n\n### Back Matter\n- Bibliography (BibLaTeX alphabetic style)\n- Index (what kinds of entries to include: terms, named theorems, named categories, notation symbols)\n- Possibly: List of Figures (commutative diagrams)\n\n### Chapter Interdependence Map\nDescribe which chapters depend on which (e.g., \"Adjoints requires Functors and Natural Transformations\"), and which chapters can be read independently for a course.\n\n---\n\n## SECTION 3: Style Guide\n\n### Proof Presentation Conventions\n- When to use a full proof vs. a proof sketch vs. \"proof omitted, see [reference]\"\n- How to handle long diagram chases: narrate each step, use numbered diagrams, avoid \"by a routine diagram chase\"\n- How to end proofs: tombstone (∎), use of `\\qed`, QED boxes\n- Inline lemmas vs. standalone lemmas\n- Style for proof by induction, proof by contradiction\n- How to handle \"the proof is dual\" situations — when acceptable, how to state it\n- Margin/side notes for key insights during proofs\n\n### Commutative Diagram Conventions\nSpecific, opinionated standards for `tikz-cd`:\n- Layout: prefer vertical arrangement for compositions, horizontal for parallel morphisms\n- Arrow styles: `->` for morphisms, `->>` for epimorphisms, `>->` for monomorphisms, `-->` for dashed (unique morphisms in UMPs), `~>` or `squiggly` for natural transformations (if using string diagrams)\n- Label placement: `description` for labels inside arrows, standard for above/below; when to abbreviate\n- Pullback/pushout corner marks: use `\\arrow[dr, phantom, \"\\lrcorner\", very near start]` convention\n- Node naming and alignment: when to use `row sep`, `column sep`, `ampersand replacement`\n- Numbering/labeling diagrams for cross-reference\n- Large diagrams: when to break across pages or use sideways environment\n- Color usage: black for main diagrams, gray for background/context arrows, red sparingly for emphasis\n\n### Exercise Difficulty Levels\nDefine a clear three-tier system:\n- ★ Routine: Direct application of definitions, should be completable in <30 minutes\n- ★★ Challenging: Requires synthesis of multiple ideas, possibly 1-3 hours\n- ★★★ Open/Research-level: Connects to open problems or requires significant original thought\n- How to mark exercises with these levels in LaTeX (enumitem with custom labels)\n- Exercises vs. Problems: exercises are immediate applications; problems are longer projects\n- Whether to include hints (in a separate hints appendix) and solutions\n\n### Notation Standards for Category Theory\nComprehensive notation table covering:\n- Categories: bold roman `𝐂` (`\\mathbf{C}`) for named categories, calligraphic `𝒞` (`\\mathcal{C}`) for generic categories — argue for one convention\n- Objects: `A, B, C` (roman) or `X, Y, Z` — when to use each\n- Morphisms: `f, g, h` for generic morphisms; arrows in diagrams\n- Functors: `F, G, H` (roman or italic); `\\mathbf{F}` if bold category, matching convention\n- Natural transformations: Greek letters `α, β, γ, η, ε` with double arrows `⇒`\n- Hom-sets: `Hom_𝐂(A, B)` vs. `𝐂(A, B)` — argue for `𝐂(A, B)` as cleaner\n- Composition order: diagrammatic `f;g` vs. standard `g∘f` — explain tradeoffs, pick one, be consistent\n- Opposite category: `𝐂^op`\n- Functor categories: `[𝐂, 𝐃]` or `𝐃^𝐂`\n- Slice/comma categories: `𝐂/A`, `(F↓G)`\n- 2-categories: `𝑪` (script bold or different font)\n- Limits/colimits: `lim`, `colim` as operators\n- Kan extensions: `Lan_K F`, `Ran_K F`\n- Adjunctions: `F ⊣ G`\n\n---\n\n## SECTION 4: Quality Standards\n\nDefine precisely what makes a chapter \"complete\" and ready for editorial review:\n\n### Minimum Requirements Per Chapter\n- **Worked examples**: At minimum 3 fully worked examples per major definition, with examples drawn from at least 2 different mathematical domains (e.g., algebra and topology)\n- **Exercises**: Minimum 8 exercises per chapter, distributed: ≥3 routine, ≥3 challenging, ≥1 at open/research level; exercises must cover all major definitions and theorems in the chapter\n- **Commutative diagrams**: At least 1 major diagram per key theorem/construction; all UMPs must have a diagram; no chapter may have zero diagrams\n- **Historical/motivational notes**: Each chapter must open with a 1–2 paragraph historical note situating the concepts; at least one named theorem must have a biographical footnote on the mathematician\n- **Cross-chapter connections**: Each chapter must contain at least 2 explicit \"See Chapter X for...\" forward/backward references\n- **Chapter summary**: End of chapter summary of key definitions and theorems (could be a list or a short paragraph)\n\n### Proof Quality Checklist\n- Every theorem has a proof or an explicit \"proof deferred to Appendix X\" or citation\n- No \"obvious\" or \"trivial\" without justification or citation\n- Diagram chases are narrated step-by-step\n- No proof ends without a QED marker\n\n### Diagram Quality Checklist\n- All tikz-cd diagrams compile without errors\n- Labels are unambiguous and consistent with surrounding text\n- Pullback/pushout corners are marked where applicable\n- Diagrams are referenced in text (\"as shown in diagram (3.2)...\")\n\n### Writing Quality Checklist  \n- Definitions are precise and use the notation established in the Notation Guide\n- No undefined notation introduced without explicit definition\n- Each example includes a verification that definitions are satisfied\n- Transitions between sections are explicit\n- Chapter introduction previews the chapter's content and its place in the larger narrative\n\n### Review Rounds\nDefine the editorial review process:\n- Draft → Author self-review → Copy-editor review (grammar, style consistency) → Technical review (math correctness) → Diagram review (tikz-cd compilation, visual clarity) → Final approval\n\n---\n\n## SECTION 5: Prerequisites Section\n\n### Required Mathematical Background\nSpecify the exact prerequisites:\n- **Abstract algebra**: Groups, rings, modules, homomorphisms, quotient structures (graduate-level, e.g., Lang's Algebra or Dummit & Foote Part I–II)\n- **Point-set topology**: Open/closed sets, continuous maps, compactness, connectedness (e.g., Munkres Part I or equivalent)\n- **Basic logic and set theory**: Functions, relations, cardinality, basic proof techniques; NOT required: formal logic or ZFC axiomatics (handled in Appendix A)\n- **Linear algebra**: Vector spaces, linear maps, tensor products (helpful but not strictly required until Chapter 5 examples)\n- **NOT required**: Algebraic topology, homological algebra, sheaf theory (though examples from these areas will appear)\n\n### Handling Varying Backgrounds\nHow the book accommodates readers with different preparation:\n- **Fast track** (strong background): Read Chapters 1–2 quickly, focus on Yoneda and Adjoints\n- **Standard track**: Linear reading; all examples are self-contained with brief reviews\n- **Slow track** (less background): Start with Appendix A on set theory, spend extra time on Chapter 1 examples before proceeding\n- **Course use**: Suggest syllabi for a one-semester course (Chapters 1–5 + selected topics), a two-semester sequence, a topics course\n- Marginal notes for \"prerequisite check\" where a concept from outside the book is used\n- Self-contained boxes for brief reviews of prerequisite material (e.g., a box reviewing the First Isomorphism Theorem when it appears as an example)\n\n### Reading Paths Diagram\nDescribe a dependency graph showing which chapters/sections depend on which, formatted as a visual aid.\n\n---\n\nFormat your output as clean Markdown with level-2 (`##`) headers for Section 2, Section 3, Section 4, and Section 5, and level-3 (`###`) subheaders within each. Be concrete, detailed, and opinionated — this is a production editorial document. Include specific LaTeX snippets or example text where it clarifies a convention.","run_in_background":true},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":202,"cache_read_input_tokens":24521,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":202},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"fa7cc145-2f78-404b-95d8-111f11645337","uuid":"6ec6d920-9345-4f00-8040-be1e7d15c0ae"}
