ization/singular, sheafification), RAPL theorem\n- **Chapter 6: Monads** — From adjunctions, algebras over a monad, Eilenberg–Moore and Kleisli categories, Beck's monadicity theorem\n- **Chapter 7: Kan Extensions** — Left and right Kan extensions, pointwise Kan extensions, density, \"all concepts are Kan extensions\"\n- **Chapter 8: Enriched Categories** (optional/advanced) — V-categories, V-functors, weighted limits, brief treatment\n- **Appendix A: Set-Theoretic Foundations** — Universes, Grothendieck universes, ZFC vs. ETCS, small vs. locally small categories\n- **Appendix B: Logic and Proof Techniques** — Brief review for readers from non-logic backgrounds\n\n### Front Matter\nDescribe in detail:\n- Title page (title, subtitle if any, author(s), date, publisher/series)\n- Copyright/colophon page\n- Dedication page\n- Preface (purpose of the book, intended audience, how to use it, acknowledgments)\n- Table of Contents\n- List of Notation (a formatted table of all symbols introduced)\n- Possibly: List of Theorems (using thmtools)\n\n### Back Matter\n- Bibliography (BibLaTeX alphabetic style)\n- Index (what kinds of entries to include: terms, named theorems, named categories, notation symbols)\n- Possibly: List of Figures (commutative diagrams)\n\n### Chapter Interdependence Map\nDescribe which chapters depend on which (e.g., \"Adjoints requires Functors and Natural Transformations\"), and which chapters can be read independently for a course.\n\n---\n\n## SECTION 3: Style Guide\n\n### Proof Presentation Conventions\n- When to use a full proof vs. a proof sketch vs. \"proof omitted, see [reference]\"\n- How to handle long diagram chases: narrate each step, use numbered diagrams, avoid \"by a routine diagram chase\"\n- How to end proofs: tombstone (∎), use of `\\qed`, QED boxes\n- Inline lemmas vs. standalone lemmas\n- Style for proof by induction, proof by contradiction\n- How to handle \"the proof is dual\" situations — when acceptable, how to state it\n- Margin/s